            AppRoutes = """["/account/security"]""",
            Tags = """["mfa","security"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Two-Step Sign-In (MFA)\n\nTwo-step sign-in adds a second lock to your QB Engineer account. Instead of just your password, you also enter a short code from an app on your phone every time you sign in.\n\n### How It Works\n\nWhen you turn this on, you link an authenticator app on your phone to your account. The app shows a fresh six-digit code that changes every 30 seconds. When you sign in, you type your password first, then the current code from the app. Because the code keeps changing and lives on your phone, someone with just your password still can't get in.\n\n### Which Apps Work\n\nAny common authenticator app works with QB Engineer:\n- **Google Authenticator** — simple, widely used\n- **Authy** — backs up to the cloud and syncs across devices\n- **Microsoft Authenticator** — works with Microsoft accounts\n- **1Password / Bitwarden** — password managers that also hold these codes\n\nDuring setup you scan a QR code with your app. If you can't scan, you can type in a short key instead.\n\n### Recovery Codes\n\nRecovery codes are one-time backup codes that let you sign in if you lose your phone or authenticator app. QB Engineer gives you a set when you turn on two-step sign-in, and you can make a new set anytime from Account > Security.\n\n**Important things to know:**\n- Each code works only once, then it's used up\n- Making a new set cancels all your old codes\n- Keep them somewhere safe, away from your phone — printed, in a password manager, or in a secure file\n- The Security page shows how many unused codes you have left\n\n### Signing In With Two-Step On\n\n1. Enter your email and password as usual\n2. You'll see a screen asking for your six-digit code\n3. Open your authenticator app and type in the current code\n4. Optionally check \"Remember this device\" to skip this step next time on a trusted computer\n5. If you can't reach your app, click \"Use recovery code\" and enter one of your backup codes\n\n### Adding a Second Device\n\nYou can link more than one app. Once two-step sign-in is on, the **Add Device** button lets you register a second app — a tablet, a backup phone, or a password manager on another computer. With two devices, a lost or wiped phone won't lock you out: you just use the other one.\n\nIn your list of **Registered Devices**, one carries a blue **Default** label. At sign-in you enter the code from that default device. If you can't reach it, use a recovery code instead. You can remove any device you no longer trust. If you remove the one marked default, another device automatically takes over as default, so you're never left without one.\n\nA good setup for the shop: make your everyday phone the default, add your password manager (1Password / Bitwarden) as a backup, and keep your printed recovery codes in a locked drawer. That way a dead battery on the floor won't strand you at sign-in.\n\n### Rules Your Admin Can Set\n\nAdmins can require two-step sign-in for certain roles (for example, Admin or Manager). When they do:\n- You'll see a note on your Security page: \"Required by organization policy\"\n- The Disable button is hidden — you can't turn it off while the rule applies to you\n- New people in a required role must set it up the next time they sign in\n- The Admin > MFA screen lists everyone, showing who has it on and whose role requires it\n\n### When to Use It\n\n- **Recommended for everyone** to protect against stolen passwords\n- **Required** when your admin has turned on a rule for your role\n- **Especially important** for Admin and Manager roles that can see sensitive data and change settings\n- **Critical** if you sign in from shared or public computers","sections":[]}"""
