o-step sign-in for all Manager and Admin users. How?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Edit each user one at a time and check 'Require MFA' on their profile"},{"id":"b","text":"Go to Admin > MFA, pick Manager and Admin under 'Required for Roles,' and click Save","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Turn on a single setting that forces it for everyone, whatever their role"},{"id":"d","text":"Send an email asking those users to turn it on themselves"}],"explanation":"On the Admin > MFA screen, choose the roles you want under 'Required for Roles' and click Save. The status table below shows who has it on and which roles require it."},{"id":"mfa8","text":"In the admin status table, a user shows 'Disabled' for two-step sign-in but 'Enforced' in the required column. What does that mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The user turned it off against the rules — no action needed"},{"id":"b","text":"Their role requires it but they haven't set it up yet — they'll be prompted next time they sign in","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It's a system error — required and off can't both be true"},{"id":"d","text":"The user was just removed from a required role"}],"explanation":"When a role requires two-step sign-in but the user hasn't set it up, the table shows Disabled plus Enforced. They'll see a warning on their Security page and must finish setup. They can't skip it."},{"id":"mfa9","text":"You have two authenticator apps registered. One shows a blue 'Default' label. What does Default mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It's the only one you can use — the other is a backup you must activate first"},{"id":"b","text":"It's the device asked for first when you sign in, before any others","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It's the one you registered first"},{"id":"d","text":"It gets push notifications while the other needs the code typed in"}],"explanation":"The default device is the one asked for first when you sign in. You can still use any registered device, but the default is the one shown first."},{"id":"mfa10","text":"You want to remove a device, but it's your only registered one. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You're stopped — you must keep at least one device"},{"id":"b","text":"A message warns that removing your only device could lock you out, and you have to confirm","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The device is removed and two-step sign-in turns itself off"},{"id":"d","text":"The device is removed and a temporary bypass code is emailed to you"}],"explanation":"Clicking the trash icon on your only device asks you to confirm and warns you could lose access. If you confirm, it's removed. Keep recovery codes saved as a backup, or turn off two-step sign-in if you no longer want it."}]}"""
