            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/account/security"]""",
            Tags = """["mfa","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Other Ways to Get Your Code (Text / Email / Security Key)\n\nAuthenticator apps are the main, recommended way, but four kinds of device are possible. Each one keeps only the details it needs.\n\n- **Authenticator app** — the only kind you can set up from Account > Security today. Your app and your account share a secret key so they can make matching six-digit codes.\n- **Security key** — a hardware key (such as a YubiKey) or a built-in option like Windows Hello or Touch ID. You tap or plug it in; there's nothing to type.\n- **Text message** — a code texted to your phone. Weaker than an app, because phone numbers can be hijacked. At sign-in the number shows partly hidden, like `***-***-1234`.\n- **Email** — a code emailed to you, a backup when nothing else is available. The address shows partly hidden, like `j***@example.com`.\n\nYou can name each device; if you don't, it just shows the kind of device. A device only works for sign-in after you finish setup by entering a code — if you quit setup early, that device is ignored.\n\n## Device Lockout & Recovery\n\nEach device keeps count of wrong codes in a row. Too many in a row lock that device for a while, which blocks anyone trying to guess your code. This is separate from the account-wide lockout that guards password and kiosk-PIN sign-in.\n\nIf you lose your authenticator, you have three ways back in:\n- **Recovery codes** — the main path. On the sign-in code screen, choose **Use recovery code** and enter one of your one-time backup codes.\n- **A second device** — if you added a backup app, just use it. Nothing is locked on the device that's simply out of reach.\n- **Admin reset** — if you have no recovery codes and no second device, an admin is the last resort. An admin can only reset or turn off two-step sign-in — never see your secret key. If your role requires two-step sign-in, you'll have to set it up again the next time you sign in.\n\n## What's Kept for Security\n\nA few details are kept so account activity can be reviewed. Your real recovery codes are never stored.\n\nFor recovery codes:\n- **Kept scrambled** — the real codes are shown once when created and never stored, so they can't be looked up later, only replaced with a new set.\n- **Used / used on** — a code is marked used the moment you sign in with it; used codes are spent for good and can't be reused.\n- **Used from** — the location a code was used from, kept for security review.\n\nFor devices, the app keeps when each was last used (shown as MM/dd/yyyy), how many wrong codes were entered, whether it's locked, and which one is your default. Making a new set of recovery codes cancels every old code right away — there's never more than one valid set.\n\n## Kiosk PIN vs Badge Scan\n\nThe kiosk PIN you set on the second card of Account > Security is its own thing, separate from your sign-in password and from two-step sign-in. It's the *second* step at the shop-floor kiosk and clock terminals: the *first* step is a physical scan — an RFID or NFC badge, or a barcode. You scan to say who you are, then enter the PIN to prove it.\n\n- The PIN is **4 to 8 digits, numbers only**, and is stored scrambled — admins can reset it but never see it.\n- There's no separate \"old PIN\" field: setting a new PIN replaces the old one, because a PIN is never entered on its own (it always follows a badge scan).\n- Wrong PINs count against the same account-wide lockout as wrong passwords — too many in a row lock the account, not just that terminal.\n- The PIN is never used to sign in through the browser, and your browser password and code are never used at the kiosk. Each one has exactly one place it's used.\n\n## Password Rules\n\nYour browser sign-in password must:\n\n- Be at least **8 characters** long\n- Include a **number**\n- Include a **lowercase letter**\n- Include an **uppercase letter**\n- Symbols are allowed but not required\n\nThese rules apply everywhere a password is set — signing up, an admin reset, and the **Change Password** card on Account > Security. To change your password, your **current password** must be correct first: a wrong one is turned away and your password stays as it was. The new password and its confirmation must match (the button stays off until they do). Changing your password doesn't sign you out, and it never touches your kiosk PIN or your two-step devices — all three are independent.","sections":[]}"""
        });

